comments.body:
@rhatdan you are right. This is what we discussed. But, then I got to thinking about the reasoning behind this decision and what we actually wanted to achieve.

The issue we discussed was that when running with Restart=Always, Podman will handle the rescheduling while we would like to leave the decision to systemd. Now, while Job disallows Restart=Always and as a result addresses this requirement, there are additional aspects required to support it such as handling of allowed number of failures.

That's why I circled back to what we actually want - when running under systemd, podman should not restart containers and instead let systemd make the decision. For that, the containers' restart policy should be never. The simple solution for this requirement is using Never as the default restart policy when running under systemd. But, as @vrothberg wrote, it is a behavior change that might break some users.
